b'' b'' b'frequently-asked questions about the open look graphical user interface.' b'' b"if your question isn't here, please try (at *least*)" b'man openwin' b'man xnews' b'man xview' b'and looking in the appropriate manuals listed in the bibliography below' b'before posting to the comp.windows.open-look, comp.windows.x or' b'alt.toolkits.xview newsgroups and/or their corresponding mailing lists.' b'' b'special notes:' b'* i have not updated this faq for the recently-announced openwindows b'due to ship later this year.' b'* yes, sun is moving to motif, along with all of cose. but the motif to' b'which they move will be a new motif, with some of the open look ui' b'features added.' b'* yes, openwindows will use dps instead of news. news is dead.' b'this means tnt is dead, too.' b'* xview and olit will be supported, but probably not enhanced after the' b"next release. i don't know if there will be a source release of" b'xview or not.' b"* the cose environment will include at least some of sun's deskset," b'ported to motif. look for calendar manager and mailtool, at least.' b'* yes, the new mailtool will be mime-compliant.' b'' b'frequently asked questions for x11 are posted to comp.windows.x monthly.' b'' b'this is version: $revision: last posted version: b'' b'contents: (in rn and trn you can use control-g to go to the next topic)' b'' b'' b'' b'' b'open look is a specification of a graphical user interface (gui).' b"a gui determines the `look and feel' of a system the shape of" b'windows, buttons and scroll-bars, how you resize things, how you' b'edit files, etc.' b'' b'the open look gui is specified, developed and maintained jointly by' b'sun microsystems and at&t (or usl?).' b'' b'see also:' b'bibliography' b'' b'openwindows is a windowing environment that conforms to the open look' b"graphical user interface specifications. it's compatible with the" b"x11 window system from mit as well as (currently) sun's news and sunview," b'so you can intermix programs written for any of those systems.' b'it comes from sun and also with system v release from certain vendors.' b'openwindows is sometimes also called openwin or xnews, after the' b'program used to start it and the main executable itself, respectively.' b"it should not be called `windows' or 'open look' or `openlook', as" b'these terms are either wrong or apply to something else.' b'a commerical openwindows source licence costs about for the server,' b'plus about for deskset, and another for tooltalk.' b'the current versions of openwindows for various platforms are:' b'sunos on sun b'solaris 1.x (sunos 4.1.x) on sparc: b'solaris (sunos on sparc: b'' b'see also:' b'mixing x11 and openwindows' b'where can i get it?' b'' b'these are all toolkits for programmers to use in developing programs' b'that conform to the open look specifications. see the bibliography' b"for documentation on the individual toolkits. here's a brief summary:" b'' b"olit was at&t's open look intrinsics toolkit for the x window system;" b'it used a widget set, and was probably the easiest for people who were' b'already x11/xt programmers to learn. you could buy the source from at&t,' b"although you didn't get the same version tht sun ship. sun includes the" b'olit library in openwindows (q.v.); it is also often included in' b'system v release it was written in c. the release of olit in' b'openwindows was olit olit support passed to usl (then a' b'division of at&t, now owned by novell), who replaced it with moolit (q.v.).' b'note that because of the nature of xt subclassing, you will probably' b'want or need olit source in order to develop a large application or' b'anything else that uses subclasses.' b'[see the proceedings of the x technical conference]' b'' b"xview is sun's toolkit for x11, written in c. xview is similar in" b"programmer interface to sunview. there's even a shell script to help" b'migrate source code from sunview to xview.\t xview is often said to be' b'the easiest toolkit to learn if you are not familiar with x windows.' b'the xview toolkit is included in openwindows, and full source is' b'available by anonymous ftp from export.lcs.mit.edu (and elsewhere).' b'the current version of xview from sun is b'despite rumours to the contrary some even from within sun the' b'xview toolkit is *not* about to be dropped by sun. xview *will* be' b'included in the next release of openwindows, unlike news.' b'on the other hand, the xview toolkit is not likely to receive as much' b'attention from sun in the future as olit.' b'' b'the news toolkit (tnt) was an object-oriented programming system based' b'on the postscript language and news. tnt implements many of the' b'open look interface components required to build the user interface of' b"an application. it's currently included in openwindows." b'' b'the current version of tnt from sun is release contains some' b"incompatibilities with `tnt' and tnt but sun are committed to" b'supporting the api, at least until they stop news support some time' b'later this year and replace it with display postscript. wail.' b"you might ask what `is committed to' means in this context; the" b'answer seems to be that it means absolutely nothing.' b'sun currently asserts that it is committed to olit, however.' b'' b'the c++ user interface toolkit (uit) consists of an object-oriented c++' b'class library layered on top of xview and a tool to generate code from' b'devguide gil files. the uit also includes features that simplify' b'event management and the use of postscript and color. it is said to be' b'compatible with openwindows v2 and v3, and presumably v3.0.1, since the' b'release mentions that it works on solaris b'uit is not an official sun-supported product but an ongoing project of' b'various people within sun. it can be found on export.lcs.mit.edu in' b'the mit contrib directory as uitv2.tar.z (use binary mode!).' b'' b"it doesn't motif is an alternative graphical user interface that" b"is being developed by osf.\tit has a `look and feel' reminiscent of" b'microsoft windows and the os/2 presentation manager. there are no non-' b'commercial motif toolkits available, although the motif source is sold' b'reasonably cheaply by osf.\talthough motif is currently available on' b'more platforms than openwindows, the open look gui is almost certainly' b'used on many more machines, simply because sun (and sysvr4) have such a' b'large installed base.' b"sun's cd/ware volume contains a roadmap for improving motif" b'applications by converting them to olit there are also notes in' b"the `periodic table' olit demo, $openwinhome/demo/olittable." b'' b'moolit is a version of olit from at&t/usl that lets users choose between' b'a motif and an open look ui feel at run-time. it will be part of system v' b'release b'' b'sun and adobe have agreed that sun will include the dps extension to x' b'in the next release of openwindows. dps is essentially a badly designed' b'hack on top of a slow level postscript interpreter intended to give a' b'very small subset of the functionality of news whilst simultaneously' b'being harder to use, as i understand it. the only real advantage it' b'has over news is that the manual is much smaller, being generally less' b'complete; dps is also available on more kinds of machine.' b'performance on our rs/6000 is not suitable for interactive work;' b'what it will be like on the sparcstation remains to be seen.' b'note that whereas x/news fonts are shared by both subsystems, the dps' b'extension to x does _not_ make type postscript fonts available to' b'ordinary x11 programs. it is not like atm on a pc in this regard.' b'(there is at least one third-party version which does make fonts' b'available, however)' b'' b'' b'they are window managers. a window manager is the part of the x window' b'system (e.g. x11) that is responsible for deciding how to lay out windows' b"on the screen, and for managing the user's interaction with the windows." b'' b'olwm is the standard open look window manager.' b"it's included with all of the openwindows (q.v.) implementations, and" b'you can also get the source by ftp, since sun donated it.' b'' b"olvwm is a version of olwm that manages a `virtual desktop' (hence the" b"`v' in its name). it shows a little map on the screen, with the" b'currently displayed area represented by a little rectangle.\t you can' b'move around by dragging the rectangle or with the arrow keys. this' b'lets you run several clients (applications) and move the display around' b'from one to the other. olvwm was derived from the openwindows olwm' b'by scott oaks; you need to have xview to compile it.' b'get olvwm from an ftp site such as export.lcs.mit.edu (in the contrib' b'directory; there are three patches).' b'' b"yes. if you use twm, for example, or mwm, you won't be able to use" b"the pin and unpin feature of olwm, and you (probably) won't see the" b'footers some windows use to display certain messages.' b'' b"if you use twm, you'll want to use the f.delete function to unpin menus" b"and get rid of programs that don't have a `quit' button when not run" b'under olwm.' b'for twm, put this in your $home/.twmrc:' b'lefttitlebutton "target" f.delete' b'where "target" is a 16x16 icon from /usr/include/x11/bitmaps.' b'alternatively, try' b'# add a menu to each window managed by twm or tvtwm' b'lefttitlebutton ":menu" f.menu "ol.menu"' b'' b'menu "ol.menu" b'"quit" f.delete' b'}' b'' b'for mwm, you can double-click on the menu icon on the left of the title' b'bar to dismiss a pop-up window (i am told).' b'' b'see the manual page for your window manager (twm, etc).' b'' b'' b'the openwindows xnews server combines sunview, news (postscript) and x11.' b'this means that it can run programs compiled for any of those systems.' b'unfortunately, it means that some openwindows programs need either news' b"or sunview support, and thus won't run on an x terminal. this includes" b'pageview in particular.' b'' b'you can use olwm or olvwm (see above) on an x terminal or a non-open-' b'windows display, and most open look clients (e.g. olit or xview ones)' b'will work perfectly well. you may find that you get complaints about' b'fonts not being found. if so, see the fonts section below.' b'if you are running the window manager built-in to an ncd terminal, you' b"may have problems with input focus; setting *input: true in the terminal's" b'xdefault file in /usr/lib/x11/xdm may or may not help.' b'' b'' b'' b'' b'.xinitrc and .xsessionrc' b'' b'the first time you run openwindows, a .xinitrc file will be created in' b'your login directory ($home). if it already exists, you might have to' b"edit it somewhat; it's simplest to move it and any other old x11 files" b'you have to another directory, and then merge the old and new files.' b'' b'if your site uses xdm, you should use .xsession instead of .xinitrc,' b"since xdm doesn't look at your .xinitrc file." b'' b'.openwin-init, .openwin-menu and .openwin-sys' b'' b'these are optional files you can create in your $home directory,' b'depending on which version of olwm or olvwm you use.' b'look in $openwinhome/lib (normally /usr/openwin/lib) for these files' b'without the leading and copy any you want to change. you may need' b'to edit your .xinitrc to get them recognized. if you are not on an' b'x terminal, you will want to run a console window (such as cmdtool -c,' b'shelltool -c, xterm -c) or chuck musciano\'s "contool" program so that' b'system output will be directed there instead of writing over your screen.' b'note that .openwin-sys is not executed unless you edit .xinitrc.' b'' b'.xdefaults' b'' b'you can put x windows resource specifications in here. in particular,' b'it is a good idea to include at least:' b'openwindows.focuslenience:\ttrue' b'*input: true' b'these allow non-icccm-compliant programs to receive input even if they' b'forget to ask for it.' b'' b"props, the program that runs when you select `properties' from the default" b'root menu under olwm or olvwm, writes your choices into .xdefaults.' b"don't put comments in .xdefaults, since `props' deletes them." b'' b'.startup.ps' b'' b'this is the news user profile file, read by openwindows (actually xnews)' b'on startup.\t this is documented in the news programming manual, near the' b'back. the most useful thing to put here is postscript code to change' b'the keyboard repeat rate, although you must be very careful, since a' b'syntax error in the postscript means that xnews will either not start up' b'at all or will get broken in strange ways.\tthe news manual gives code' b'that is both incorrect and insufficient.' b'warning: things in this file rarely work on both openwindows and b'' b'note that the mouse speed is best set in your .xinitrc with xset m; see' b'the man page for xset ("man xset", and "xset -help") for more information.' b'' b"here's what $home/.startup.ps should look like if you want a delay of" b'about a third of a second microseconds), and a repeat rate of' b'twenty or so keys per second microseconds between repeats) for' b"openwindows you'll have to experiment a bit because the repeattime" b"is the delay between keys sent, and thus doesn't include the time to" b'process each key, which is probably higher on my than on your' b'supersparc gti injection again, this is for openwindows b'' b"% don't want the demos see p. xxxii of news toolkit reference manual" b'% /includedemos? false def' b'' b'userprofile begin' b'/keyrepeatthresh timeval storetimeval def' b'/keyrepeattime timeval storetimeval def' b'% note: and differ greatly...' b'end' b'' b'you must also have a .user.ps file in the same directory, like this:' b'' b'/news findpackage beginpackage' b'/tntcore findpackage beginpackage' b'/tnt findpackage beginpackage' b'' b'classrepeatkeys pop\t% force repeat.ps to autoload' b'' b'endpackage endpackage endpackage' b'' b'if you change these parameters, you can test them without restarting the' b'openwindows server like this:' b'$ psh -i .startup.ps' b'welcome to x11/news version3' b'$ psh -i' b'welcome to x11/news version3' b'/classinit classrepeatkeys send' b'%%% now press control-d' b'' b'you can also either of these two files (.startup.ps and .user.ps) to make' b'the root window be "retained", so that a postscript drawing on the' b"background won't be erased when you move windows:" b'frambuffer /retained true put' b'will do this. note that this may increase the amount of memory used' b'by the news server (xnews) dramatically.' b'' b'see also:' b"trouble shooting: it won't let me type" b'trouble shooting: is there an easy way to edit xdefaults?' b'environment variables' b'' b'you can use xmodmap to change the mouse buttons, but be prepared for one' b'or two occasional surprises. see also "man xview" for a list of' b'keybindings you can change, at least for xview programs.' b'' b'with openwindows you can use defaultsedit to set the mouse mappings' b'and then let sunview handle them. the status returned by svenv should' b'tell you whether your server is running under sunview or not; put this' b'in your .xinitrc:' b'' b'if eval `svenv -env`' b'then' b'xmodmap -e "pointer b'input_from_defaults' b'else' b'xmodmap -e "pointer b'fi' b'' b'' b'' b"run screenblank from /etc/rc.local if you can; it's a boring but" b"effective screen saver. see `man screenblank'." b"under solaris you'll need to copy screenblank from an older system, as" b"it's not supplied. then add a new file in /etc/rc2.d to make the system" b'run screenblank automatically.' b'' b'' b'' b'to go from xterm to textedit (say):' b'* select the text you want to copy by dragging the select mouse button' b'in xterm' b"* press copy in the xterm (this key is l6, or meta+c (the o'reilly" b'xview manual gets this wrong)' b'* move to the textedit window, and press paste (l8 or meta+v)' b'' b"if this doesn't work, see trouble shooting: cut and paste" b'' b'to go the other way, from textedit to xterm:' b'* select the text in textedit. no need to use copy' b'* move to the xterm window and press adjust (the middle mouse button).' b'* you can also use the copy/cut and paste buttons.' b'' b'' b'quick copy within textedit, mailtool, etc:' b'* click select to get a text caret where you want the copied text to go' b'* press and hold down the paste (or cut) button' b"* select the text you want to copy/move. you'll see that it's underlined" b'or crossed out, as appropriate. (in the jed demo it goes grey)' b'* let go of the paste (or cut) button.' b'* the text you underlined or crossed out appears at the insert caret.' b'' b'drag and drop to move a selection' b'* select the text you want to copy or move, by dragging or multiple-' b'clicking the select or adjust mouse button' b'* put the mouse pointer anywhere within the selection' b'* press and hold down down the select mouse button, and move the mouse' b"pointer a little to the right; you'll see the cursor changes to be the" b'first letters of the text (or some other icon).' b'* still holding select down, move the mouse over the point where you want' b'to drop the text' b'* you may see the mouse pointer change to a rifle-sight or target, to show' b"that it's ok to drop things here" b'* let go of select, and the text is moved.\tthis works in text fields of' b'dialogue boxes as well as in text subwindows.' b'' b'drag and drop to copy a selection' b'* this is the same as using drag and drop to move a selection, except that' b'you must hold the control key down as well as the select mouse button.' b'' b'' b'see the man page for textedit(1) for some of them.' b'in general, the editing/moving commands go in the opposite direction when' b'shifted e.g. ctrl+w deletes a word, and ctrl+w deletes the word to the' b'right of the insert point.' b'' b'meta-i include file\t meta-f find selection (forward/backward)' b'' b'ctrl-a start of line\t ctrl-< back word' b'ctrl-e end of line\t ctrl- forward word' b'ctrl-w delete word\t ctrl-u delete to start/end of line' b'ctrl-return move to end/start of document' b'' b"see the o'reilly xview reference manual for a list of some of the default" b'keys; see also the olwm or olvwm manual page.' b'' b'' b'see the manual page for shelltool.' b'' b'contact sunsoft (or sun) and ask for the catalyst open look guide,' b'which lists over pages of applications, and also the _huge_' b'catalyst listing of products for suns, updated six-monthly.' b'' b"sun's free cdware cd/roms each contain demo versions of several popular" b'open look applications. often you can simply contact the vendor' b'concerned to have the license upgraded from demo, and receive the full' b'product documentation.' b'' b"sunpics produces a cd/rom for newsprint users, printer's pallate, which" b'contains newsprint drivers for a variety of printers and plotters, as' b'well as scaleable fonts that you can license.' b'' b'there is a separate faq posting in comp.windows.open-look that lists' b'copy, including open look ui application list in the subject for a' b'faster reply.' b'' b'' b'yes, cm_delete, cm_insert and cm_lookup; these all have manual pages.' b'if "man cm_delete" doesn\'t work or gives strange messages, see under' b'trouble shooting: strange error messages, below.' b'' b'the best way is:' b'$ cd' b'$ cp /usr/lib/.textswrc b'$ chmod +w .textswrc' b'edit .textswrc (use vi, textedit, or whatever you prefer)' b'add the follwing:' b'key_right(3) filter' b'cat ~/.signature' b'(you might need to change to $home)' b'' b'now pressing r3 will insert your .signature file.' b'' b'' b'' b'' b"yes, under either solaris or (i'm not sure which)." b'or, not yet, in other words.' b'' b"if you have framemaker there is a utility to import them, i'm told." b'the fonts supplied with openwindows are fully hinted, though, and' b'comparing them to the microsoft windows and apple truetype fonts is' b'interesting... the f3 font format is described in a publication from the' b'sun openfonts group, listed in the bibliography below. documentation on' b'the unbundled version of typescaler i